content.description: Climb the left side of the face starting on pocket shared with Quaid (to your right) and a left facing flake. Climb through a horizontal and another pocket to top it out.
content.location: On the second and left most boulder you come to when walking downhill from the Moby's Dick Boulder, this is the left most line on the featured face. Just left of Quaid.

content.description: Sit start on a pinch created by the parallel vertical cracks. Make a long move to the lip of the roof and mantle.  Avoid the temptation to bail left or right, and use only hands and feet on the roof-block to pull yourself completely over the edge.
content.location: From Moby's Dick, continue down the trail past Quaid and Clarity.  This route is on the back the block that contains Clarity.

content.description: Start on an undercling jug directly behind the large tree.  Utilize a pinch to reach a jug, then make another fun move to an easy topout.  This problem avoids the left crack entirely.
content.location: Directly behind the large tree

content.description: A fairly long problem with really good movement. Start on an undercling and climb past an incut flake to a jug. Make a powerful move from the jug into a really cool gaston move and then to another jug to top out the boulder.
content.location: Located on the boulder below "Moby's Dick" towards the right side of the block and a little to the right of a big tree.

content.description: Start standing using an undercling and an undercling/sidepull with thin feet. Move up and right to a crimp rail and back left to a sidepull. Throw to the top and top out.
content.location: On the right side of the vertical face between Clarity and Wang Gang.

content.description: Stand-start on two opposing side-pulls. Made a decent sized move to an invisible jug.  Then make a move to a small edge and power through to the top.  It can be exhilarating on sighting it without scoping out the top out holds, but they are definitely there.
content.location: The most downhill of the three Moby's Dick Area boulders just to the right of chossy looking rock.

content.description:
Description from the Falcon guidebook:

"Characterized by thin, balance-y moves on bad holds. Start just left of the flat talus on a pinch and follow thin edges up and slightly left to the top."

The feet are actually quite good, as slab goes, and there were a couple of nice edges, but reaching them may be height dependent.

Overall a fun problem that would be more fun if it was longer.
content.location: Check out the snapshot of the area map included in the photos.

content.description: Start left hand on sloping hueco and right on the best part of the sloper near Moby’s mantel start. Jump for three finger edge at lip, catch it, and mantel. In my opinion, is either a piece of cake or impossible depending on conditions, Power, and luck.
content.location: In between Moby Project and Moby’s Mantel.

content.description: An intimidating climb consisting of big moves on big holds. Start under the roof on on a left facing flake. Move up through jugs to a good, and often wet knob in the middle of the roof. Make a huge, powerful move out past the lip of the roof to a good hold and another big move up left to an even better hold. From here, stick the lip of the boulder and make a committing topout. The landing to this problem has a large stump and a sloping boulder in just the wrong places. A bunch of pads can help level the stump area out and a spotter or two can help you land upright with the boulder under you.
content.protection: Several pads, Spotters. This problem has a very bad landing.
content.location: On the farthest downhill boulder in the Moby's Dick area. Locate the large roof that is on the river side of the block.

content.description: Start a few feet left of the large rock that makes up Moby's Dick under a green streak. Step onto some good footholds at the base of the slab and follow smears and a few slopey crimps up the streak trending slighly left. Avoid the jug sidepulls used on Guevara. Topout.
content.protection: One pad will work, but there are some pointy rocks.
content.location: On the main Moby's Dick Boulder, this climb starts a few feet left of the large rock that makes up Moby's Dick under a green streak.

content.description: Sit start using a good pocket and an undercling. Continue upward using a few pockets, a horizontal, and an edge to a nice topout. Avoid the holds way left on Wang Gang.
content.location: On the second and left most boulder you come to when walking downhill from the Moby's Dick Boulder, this is the right most line on the featured face.

content.description:
Start sitting using a high square knob pinch and a sidepull for hands. Move up through opposing sidepulls to a slopey topout.

This route is #24 on Moby’s Dick Tier 1: Boulder 3 in the Tilted Tree Area of the Brayack and Keenan Falcon Guidebook.
content.location: In the middle of the vertical face left of Clarity. Look for the noticeable square knob.

content.description: Start on a right crimpy sidepull and a left sloping crimp. Use good smears and small crimp edges to move up the slight trough while avoiding the sloping bulge "arete" on the left. Topout.
content.location: This line follows a slight indentation in the slab about 8 feet right of the large crack on the left of the Moby Slab boulder.

content.description:
Start standing just left of the arete using a large flat edge for hands. Move up the face just left of the arete and topout. The route is pretty much a single cool move (the move is slightly harder if you don't use hands on the arete).

This route is #12 on Boulder 1: Moby's Dick Boulder in the Moby's Dick Area in the Brayack & Keenan Falcon guidebook.
content.location:
From the far left end of the Moby Slab, turn around and walk between 2 small boulders (not climbable. Head about 20 ft right to the first climbable boulder. This route is on the far right side of the downhill face, to the right of the large flat talus and just left of the arete. The large flat hold is noticeable.

This boulder will be halfway between Moby Slab And Moby's Dick Area: Tier 1 and left of both.

content.description: Variation of Moby's Tail. Same start as Moby's Tail but from the featured section veer left through the good left facing sidepull flake to an easy topout.
content.location: Just left of the detached block Moby's Dick is on.

content.description: Stand start with hands on a flake just left of the detached block that Moby’s Dick is on. Veer slightly left through a featured section and then straight up from the features getting high feet through a thin face and top out.
content.location: Just left of the detached block Moby's Dick is on.

content.description: Start on a knob and pocket. Avoiding the awkward talus, move right past a gaston and sloper to a side pull. Continue right past a pocket to a strenuous mantel. SS TO.
content.location: Route starts on the corner of the large boulder, about 10 yards to the right of Moby's Dick Problem.

content.description: Classic! One of the most popular routes at Coopers. Sit start and ascend the leaning block using some good holds and a few heel hooks. Make a big move to the lip of the boulder and top out.
content.location: The obvious leaning block on the Moby's Dick boulder

content.description:
Fun problem underneath the block that forms "Moby's Dick". Sit Start and layback the overhang to a top out.

Pumpy, but not as technical as Moby's Dick. Crux is probably near the top when the feet get a bit smoother than the start.
content.location: Look under Moby's Dick.

content.description:
Start standing with thin crimps for hands that feel great because it's slab. Find feet and go up through more thin crimps because what else would there be on slab. Easy topout because it’s slab.

This route is #5 on the Moby Slab in the Brayack & Keenan guidebook.
content.location: Route 2 feet left of the Moby’s Dick arete on the slab portion of the detached block.

content.description:
Start on the left facing flake and a sloping right sidepull.  Follow the flake to an undercling and pleasant jugs to the top.

This route is # 8 on the Moby Slab in the Brayack & Keenan guidebook.
content.location: Follows the flake system directly over the tree root

content.description:
Start on the jug ledge left of the large tree.  Mantel and use holds out high and left to reach the top...then mantel again!

This route is # 10a on the Moby Slab in the Brayack & Keenan guidebook.
content.location: Starts about 10 ft left of the large tree

content.description:
Get on this thing! This excellent route is not found in the guidebook and there is no good reason for it.

A right leaning hand crack that narrows to fingers after a jug. Start by slamming two solid hands in for the sit start and jam or lay back your way up to the finger crack. If you are chasing the grade, avoid the obvious jug, keeping your hands/fingers strictly in the crack.

If you choose to use the jug, the climb is still excellent and goes at around V1. This is a good option for those learning to jam!

**Note**

I wasn't sure what to grade this thing. It felt like a Cooper's Rock V2, but a friend recommended the grade of V3. I opted for V2+, but am excited for more crushers to get on this and give their input.
content.location: Locate the climbs "Quaid", "Wang Gang", or "Clarity". Walk to climbers left and around the corner of this boulder. Walk up to the hill about 15 feet. This climb will be on your right.

content.description: Sit start with a left hand 4-finger pocket and a right hand on a sloping crimp.  Make a long move straight up to good holds at the lip, then top out.
content.location: This route starts about 5 ft right of the arete on the black-spotted face.  It is ~25 ft climbers left of Clarity.

content.description: Begins just left of the arete on a vertical slot and tri-pocket feature.  Make your way relatively straight up to a finger lock / gaston move to gain the horn a couple feet left of the arete. Figure out how to top-out and don't look back!  cool technical route with oddly shaped holds that all feel super solid.
content.location: Starts opposite of Quad in the triangular alcove on tier 1 of moby's dick area (boulder south of moby's dick).

content.description:
Start on the large talus.  Follow jugs through inward opposing flakes to an easy topout.

This route is # 6 on the Moby Slab in the Brayack & Keenan guidebook
content.location: Starts on the large triangular talus

content.description: Sit start and ascend the arete using several pockets and a few edges. Near the top, find a few good holds on the left side of the arete and make a committing mantle topout.
content.location: On the first and right most boulder you come to when walking downhill from the Moby's Dick Boulder, this is the obvious pocketed arete on the left end of the boulder.

content.description:
This route isn’t that bad if you don’t mind sharp holds. Start standing with hands on the obvious flake feature that comes to a point and move up and slightly left to a pinch on a protruding feature and find the hidden edge/pocket.  Figure out your feet and body position and take your choice of betas either straight up to a sloper or up and slightly right to a slopey crimp at the lip (you’ll probably end up using both of these holds anyways). Find your inner peace as you go straight up from there to a mild scramble of a top-out.

*Update*: the start hold has broken on this route. The route is still doable at the grade but now you start on the flat crimp where the start hold used to be and an edge just left of it.
content.location: On the second (lowest) tier of the Moby Dick Area this route is around the corner right of the roof that holds Roof of Death. This route is in the middle of this face. Look for the flake feature that comes to a point.

content.description:
Start on the jug ledge left of the large tree.  Traverse right to the left facing flake and ascend the jugs to the top.

This route is # 10 on the Moby Slab in the Brayack & Keenan guidebook.
content.location: Starts about 10 ft left of the large tree

content.description:
Start standing to the right of the arete and using holds on the arete (and only on the arete), move up and top out. Your body should stay right of the arete for the whole climb.

This route is #12a on Boulder 1: Moby's Dick Boulder in the Moby's Dick Area in the Brayack & Keenan Falcon guidebook.
content.location:
From the far left end of the Moby Slab, turn around and walk between 2 small boulders (not climbable. Head about 20 ft right to the first climbable boulder. This route goes up the right side of the arete that is on the left side of the face as you are approaching  the boulder.

This route the right side of the arete and the route to the left of this (Mystic) goes up the left side of this arete.

This boulder will be halfway between Moby Slab And Moby's Dick Area: Tier 1 and left of both.

content.description:
Start as for "Roof of Death" on a large left facing flake. Move up to the horizontal crack and traverse to the far left end. Reach up to edges on the vertical face and make committing moves with crafty footwork to gain jugs at the top. Finish with an

easy but well deserved topout.
content.location: On the farthest downhill boulder in the Moby's Dick area. Locate the large roof that is on the river side of the block.

content.description:
Sit start on opposing edges.  Power to right flake and work your way up using heel hooks and good holds.  Move over slightly bulging edge to topout.

V3 variation eliminates the back right flake.
content.location: Around the corner from Wang Gang/Qaid rock face.

content.description:
Start on very thin edges under a prominent undercling feature. Move up with thin feet to the undercling and then use a sidepull and thin crack to get to great ledges for an easy topout. Stay to the right of the large left facing flake and to the left of several thin sidepull features for both hands and feet. If you're pretty much standing on nothing and praying you don’t slip... You’ll know you’re doing it right. Stand start.

This route is #7 on the Moby Slab in the Brayack & Keenan guidebook.
content.protection: Kind of a bad landing bring a pad.
content.location: 10 feet left of the gigantic talus. Under the prominent undercling feature just before the next flake.
